  "text": "Accelerometer-based walking speed estimation methods can be divided into two categories: (a) machine learning-based methods and (b) model-based methods. Our work employs a machine learning approach, which has the potential to exploit associative information within data beyond an explicit model chosen by the system designer. However, most previous work that applies machine learning methods to walking speed estimation assumes that there are one or more accelerometers at fixed positions on the body [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . For example, Vathsangam et al. [CITATION_3] use Gaussian process regression to estimate walking speed from one accelerometer fixed on a subject's hip. In contrast, our work estimator does not assume that the accelerometer, embedded in the user's mobile device, is in any particular position.",
